  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\"). This is typically done by disguising the source of the money, changing its form, or moving it to a place where it is less likely to attract attention.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is a serious criminal offense under federal law, governed by statutes such as the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)**. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Severe fines**: Depending on the amount of money involved, fines can reach into the hundreds of thousands or even millions of dollars.\n- **Prison sentences**: Convictions can result in significant prison time, often up to 20 years per count.\n- **Asset forfeiture**: The government can seize assets connected to the laundering activity.\n\nAdditionally, money laundering is often prosecuted alongside other crimes, such as drug trafficking, fraud, or terrorism financing, which can lead to even harsher penalties. If you are facing charges related to money laundering, it is crucial to consult with a qualified attorney to understand your rights and options.",
